```{r, include = FALSE}
knitr::opts_chunk$set(
  fig.path = "figures/susceptible-depletion-",
  collapse = TRUE,
  comment = "#>",
  eval = TRUE,
  cache = TRUE,
  message = FALSE,
  warning = FALSE,
  dpi = 330
)
```

The renewal expectation model in `epinowcast` can optionally account for
susceptible depletion.
Given an initial susceptible population, transmission is scaled by the remaining
susceptible fraction, so the effective reproduction number bends down as the
pool depletes.
This vignette demonstrates the adjustment on simulated data where depletion
plays a clear role, fitting the expectation-only model with and without it.

```{r setup}
library(epinowcast)
library(data.table)
library(ggplot2)

set.seed(2024)
```

## A depleting epidemic on simulated data

We simulate a single well-mixed population of `N = 4000` susceptibles seeded
with a few cases and driven by a renewal process with a fixed generation time
and a constant reproduction number.
Because the population is small, the susceptible pool is meaningfully depleted
over the epidemic and the realised growth slows even though transmissibility is
constant.

```{r simulate}
simulate_depleting <- function(population, rt, generation_time, n_days,
                                seed_cases = 5) {
  gt_n <- length(generation_time)
  rgt <- rev(generation_time)
  inc <- rep(seed_cases, n_days)
  cum_cases <- sum(inc[seq_len(gt_n)])
  for (i in (gt_n + 1):n_days) {
    infectiousness <- sum(inc[(i - gt_n):(i - 1)] * rgt)
    remaining <- max(0, population - cum_cases)
    inc[i] <- remaining * (1 - exp(-rt * infectiousness / max(1, remaining)))
    cum_cases <- cum_cases + inc[i]
  }
  list(incidence = inc, attack_size = cum_cases)
}

population <- 4000
gt <- c(0.3, 0.4, 0.3)
sim <- simulate_depleting(population, rt = 1.7, generation_time = gt,
                          n_days = 45)

obs <- data.table(
  reference_date = as.Date("2021-01-01") + seq_along(sim$incidence) - 1,
  confirm = rpois(length(sim$incidence), sim$incidence)
)
obs[, report_date := reference_date]

cat("Realised attack size:", round(sim$attack_size),
    "of", population, "susceptibles\n")
```

The realised attack size consumes a large fraction of the population, so
depletion is not negligible.

## Preprocessing

We treat the simulated counts as fully reported (no reporting delay) so the
expectation model is the only component being tested.

```{r preprocess}
pobs <- enw_preprocess_data(
  enw_complete_dates(obs, max_delay = 2), max_delay = 2
)
```

## Fitting with and without susceptible depletion

We fit the same renewal model twice: once with the susceptible-depletion
adjustment (`population = N`) and once without it (the default).
Both use a weekly random walk on the log reproduction number.

```{r fit}
fit_opts <- enw_fit_opts(
  save_warmup = FALSE, pp = FALSE, chains = 2,
  iter_warmup = 500, iter_sampling = 500, adapt_delta = 0.95,
  max_treedepth = 12, show_messages = FALSE, refresh = 0
)

nowcast_adjusted <- epinowcast(
  pobs,
  expectation = enw_expectation(
    r = ~ rw(week), generation_time = gt, population = population, data = pobs
  ),
  obs = enw_obs(family = "poisson", data = pobs),
  fit = fit_opts
)

nowcast_unadjusted <- epinowcast(
  pobs,
  expectation = enw_expectation(
    r = ~ rw(week), generation_time = gt, data = pobs
  ),
  obs = enw_obs(family = "poisson", data = pobs),
  fit = fit_opts
)
```

## Comparing the recovered attack size

We extract the posterior latent cases (`exp_llatent`) from each fit and compare
the recovered cumulative attack size with the known truth.

```{r attack-size}
attack_size <- function(nowcast, label) {
  draws <- posterior::as_draws_matrix(nowcast$fit[[1]]$draws("exp_llatent"))
  total <- rowSums(exp(draws))
  data.table(
    model = label, mean = mean(total),
    q5 = quantile(total, 0.05), q95 = quantile(total, 0.95)
  )
}

attack <- rbind(
  attack_size(nowcast_adjusted, "adjusted"),
  attack_size(nowcast_unadjusted, "unadjusted")
)
knitr::kable(attack, digits = 0, caption = paste(
  "Recovered cumulative attack size. True value:", round(sim$attack_size)
))
```

The adjusted model recovers the realised attack size, attributing the slowdown
to a shrinking susceptible pool.
The unadjusted model has to explain the same slowdown through a falling
reproduction number, which biases its reconstruction of the latent epidemic.

## Estimated latent epidemic

```{r plot-latent, fig.cap = "Posterior mean latent cases under each model against the simulated truth."}
latent_summary <- function(nowcast, label) {
  s <- nowcast$fit[[1]]$summary("exp_llatent", mean = mean)
  data.table(model = label, time = seq_len(nrow(s)), mean = exp(s$mean))
}

latent <- rbind(
  latent_summary(nowcast_adjusted, "adjusted"),
  latent_summary(nowcast_unadjusted, "unadjusted")
)
truth <- data.table(
  model = "truth", time = seq_along(sim$incidence), mean = sim$incidence
)

ggplot(rbind(latent, truth), aes(x = time, y = mean, colour = model)) +
  geom_line() +
  labs(x = "Time", y = "Latent cases", colour = NULL) +
  theme_bw()
```

## Fitting an uncertain population

When the initial susceptible population is unknown, it can be estimated by
setting `population_uncertain = TRUE`.
`population` then provides the median of a LogNormal prior with coefficient of
variation `population_cv`.

```{r uncertain}
nowcast_uncertain <- epinowcast(
  pobs,
  expectation = enw_expectation(
    r = ~ rw(week), generation_time = gt, population = population,
    population_uncertain = TRUE, population_cv = 0.5, data = pobs
  ),
  obs = enw_obs(family = "poisson", data = pobs),
  fit = fit_opts
)

pop_post <- nowcast_uncertain$fit[[1]]$summary("expr_pop_est")
knitr::kable(
  pop_post[, c("variable", "mean", "q5", "q95")],
  digits = 0, caption = paste("Estimated population. True value:", population)
)
```

The estimated population brackets the true value, recovering it from the
depletion signal alone.

## Assumptions

The adjustment assumes a single well-mixed population per group with no waning
of immunity and no births or deaths, so the susceptible pool is only ever
depleted by modelled latent cases.
It applies only to the renewal path (`length(generation_time) > 1`).
See `?enw_expectation` for the `population`, `population_floor`,
`population_uncertain`, and `population_cv` arguments.
